1. Introduction to Linux Volumes and AWS EBS

Interview: Linux volumes are storage units mounted to directories for data management, while AWS EBS is a persistent block storage
service that provides virtual disks for EC2 instances.

What are Linux Volumes?

A volume in Linux is a storage unit or partition where files and data are stored.
Volumes can be:

Physical disks (/dev/xvda)
Partitions (/dev/xvda1)
Logical volumes (LVM)

They are mounted to directories like:

Bash
/mnt
/data
/home

Common Linux Volume Concepts
Term	              Meaning
Disk	              Physical storage device
Partition	          Divided section of a disk
File System	        Structure used to store files (ext4, xfs)
Mount Point	        Directory where volume is attached

Useful Linux Volume Commands
Bash
a. lsblk: Shows attached disks and partitions
b. df -h: Shows mounted storage usage
c. mount: Displays mounted volumes


2. Physical Vs Logical Volume vs Volume groups in Linux

Interview: In Linux LVM, a Physical Volume is the actual disk or partition, a Volume Group is a storage pool created from physical volumes,
and a Logical Volume is a virtual partition created from the volume group for user data.

In order to check the logical volume in linux, in ec2 instance switch user as root user and run commands.

E.g. ubuntu@ip-172-31-87-248:~$ sudo su
root@ip-172-31-87-248:/#lvm
lvm>pvcreate /dev/xvdf /dev/xvdg /dev/xvdh      #mounting logical volumes xvdf, xvdg and xvdh as logical volumes
lvm>pvs      #to check them if created
lvm> vgcreate tws_vg /dev/xvdf /dev/xvdg      #tws volume group
lvm>vgs        # to check volume group created (10gb+12gb=22gb or 21.9gb)
lvm>lvcreate -L 10G -n tws_lv tws_vg
lvm>pvdisplay      #displays physical volumes
lvm>vgdisplay      #displays volume groups
lvm>lvdisplay      #displays logical volumes
lvm>exit

root@ip-172-31-87-248:/#lvs
root@ip-172-31-87-248:/#mkdir /mnt/tws_lv_mount
root@ip-172-31-87-248:/#mkfs.ext4 /dev/tws_vg/tws_lv      #formats
root@ip-172-31-87-248:/#mount /dev/tws_vg/tws_lv /mnt/tws_lv_mount
root@ip-172-31-87-248:/#lsblk
root@ip-172-31-87-248:/#df -h
root@ip-172-31-87-248:/#cd /mnt/tws_lv_mount
root@ip-172-31-87-248/mnt/tws_lv_mount:#mkdir devops
root@ip-172-31-87-248/mnt/tws_lv_mount:#ls
devops   lost+found
root@ip-172-31-87-248/mnt/tws_lv_mount:#cd devops
root@ip-172-31-87-248/mnt/tws_lv_mount/devops:#vim hi.txt
write something
root@ip-172-31-87-248/mnt/tws_lv_mount/devops:#cd
root@ip-172-31-87-248~:# cat /mnt/tws_lv_mount/devops/hi.txt
hello world        #displays the text      #this shows now we can access the content from anywhere

root@ip-172-31-87-248~:# umount mnt/tws_lv_mount      #unmounts the logical volume
After this can't access the hi.txt file, but re mount
root@ip-172-31-87-248~:# mount mnt/tws_lv_mount

1. Physical Volume (PV)

A Physical Volume is the actual physical storage device or partition used by LVM.

👉 Examples:

Hard disk
SSD
Disk partition

Example device:

/dev/xvdf
/dev/sdb1
📦 2. Volume Group (VG)

A Volume Group is a pool of storage created by combining one or more Physical Volumes.

👉 Think of it as:

“A storage container made from multiple disks.”

Example:

vg_data
📂 3. Logical Volume (LV)

A Logical Volume is a virtual partition created from a Volume Group.

👉 This is what users actually use and mount.

Example:

/dev/vg_data/lv_backup

Real-world Analogy
LVM Component	            Analogy
Physical Volume	          Individual bricks
Volume Group	            Entire storage warehouse
Logical Volume	          Rooms created inside warehouse

Useful Commands
A. Create Physical Volume
pvcreate /dev/sdb

B. Create Volume Group
vgcreate vg_data /dev/sdb

C. Create Logical Volume
lvcreate -L 5G -n lv_backup vg_data      #create logical volume of size 5GB lv_backup from volume group vg_data

✅ Advantages of LVM
Easy resizing of storage
Flexible disk management
Combine multiple disks
Snapshots and backups

3. Mounting Volumes in Linux

root@ip-172-31-87-248~:#mkdir tws_disk_mount
root@ip-172-31-87-248~:#cd /mnt/
root@ip-172-31-87-248/mnt:#ls
tws_disk_mount   tws_lv_mount

root@ip-172-31-87-248/mnt:#mkfs -t ext4 /dev/xvdh    #make format 3rd physical volume
root@ip-172-31-87-248/mnt:#cd
root@ip-172-31-87-248~:#mount /dev/xvdh /mnt/tws_disk_mount
root@ip-172-31-87-248~:#df -h      #check if it is mounted

Resizing the logical volume

root@ip-172-31-87-248~:#lvm
lvm>lvextend +5G /dev/tws_vg/tws_lv    #will resize from 10Gb to 15Gb
lvm>exit
root@ip-172-31-87-248~:#df -h          #check the volume storage using this command
root@ip-172-31-87-248~:#lsblk          # and this command


4. Managing AWS EBS on EC2 instances

What is AWS EBS?
📦 EBS = Elastic Block Store

Amazon Web Services EBS is a block storage service used with EC2 instances.

Think of it as a virtual hard disk attached to an EC2 server.

Features of EBS
Persistent storage (data remains after reboot)
Can attach/detach volumes
Supports backups using snapshots
Different volume types (gp3, io1, st1)

How EBS Works with EC2
1. Create EC2 instance
2. Attach EBS volume
3. Linux detects volume (lsblk)
4. Format volume
5. Mount volume to a directory

Basic EBS Setup Commands (Linux)
1️⃣ Check attached volume
lsblk

2️⃣ Format volume
sudo mkfs -t ext4 /dev/xvdf      #naming always starts with xvdf, cvdg etc. xvd(a-e) is not used by users

3️⃣ Create mount directory
sudo mkdir /data

4️⃣ Mount volume
sudo mount /dev/xvdf /data

5️⃣ Verify
df -h

🎯 Real DevOps Use Cases
Store application data
Database storage
Persistent storage for servers
Backup and disaster recovery

